Panto is well and truly back in Blackpool! Last night we were kindly invited to watch Sleeping Beauty at The Grand Theatre Blackpool,  and what a night we had! 
 
It was by far the most impressive pantomime I’ve seen in a long time. Audience participation was high, costumes  we’re colourful and the actors had everyone laughing in their seats every few seconds!

Keeping in line with the traditional fairy tale this high energy performance had many twists along the way, including tiktok dances, eggs on heads, jokes for parents, amazing use of props and a cast that oozed non stop energy.  Oh and of course not forgetting a very handsome Prince! 

This all age 2.5 hour show was a fantastic way to kick of the festive season and from the giggles and gasps in the audience I think it’s fair to say everyone was having a fabulous night! 

You can book your tickets to this amazing Panto at  www.blackpoolgrand.co.uk Showing on and until Jan 1st.

This morning we went slightly off the well worn tourist track and visited the township of Mondesa with @explorer_tours_safari_namibia 

Mondesa is less than a ten minute drive from where we are staying in #swakopmund but couldn’t be more different. 

We learnt about the different tribes in Namibia from Ovambo, Damara, Herero and the Ovahimba people. We learnt (or tried to learn) some local click words, were warmly welcomed by a women’s collective and bought some Christmas decorations, we had a fascinating talk on the clothing still worn by local Herero women and then were treated to a selection of foods to eat including the local mopane worms - full credit to Izzy for trying! 

Fascinating morning.

Arrived at Grootberg Lodge @journeysnamibia yesterday which is on the edge of the Etendeka Plateau. It’s impossible to get a scale of the place from the photos, but it’s vast! It’s also run as a community project, by the local people for the benefit of the local people, and funds the majority of the community. 

Last night Matt and I did a sunset tour of the plateau and drank G&T’s whilst the sun went down: an early anniversary moment as it’s our thirteenth wedding anniversary today.

Today was our first afternoon in @etoshanationalpark we have another full day tomorrow driving West to East. We were incredibly lucky to be pointed in the direction of a pride of four lions by another kind driver. Incredible. We arrived just as they decided to walk across our path on the road.

We also saw a hyena, a jackal, giraffe, elephants, many antelope, desert squirrel and even a tortoise!

Let’s see if me and the girls can find a rhino tomorrow too. There is definitely one around with her baby.

At @okonjima_nature_reserve today it’s all been about leopard tracking 🐆 and we found Kit in the 23,000 hectare reserve! Isn’t he a beauty. Took around 2 hours to find him. He was hiding under a tree and was definitely watching something! 

We were also lucky enough to see two rhino on the road on the way in, charging at each other! They were in part of the reserve they shouldn’t really be in so we were really lucky to stumble upon them! 

The reserve is also home to giraffe ( we saw lots) antelope of various types, wilderbeast and even a very rare spotted genet with three babies that the staff called us away from dinner to see as she was just outside the reception. 

What another amazing day! 

We are up at dawn tomorrow to head to the @africat_foundation to hopefully see some cheetahs! 🐆 Alarm set for 5.15am!

And with that the 2022 season is over!

Happy New Years Eve folks.

And that’s a wrap on our #NamibiaAdventure - we’re at @joesbeerhouse for a last meal before our flight home because it was where we had our first meal! 

Springbok, Kudu and Zebra on the menu. Will be a while til we eat that again. 

Our stay last night at @naankusecollection was interesting. It’s a wildlife foundation, but after a week of seeing animals in their natural habitat it’s hard to see them in smaller enclosures. There’s a reason for it though: the animals are all rehabilitated and can’t actually live in the wild, the money raised from guests like us visiting supports the work the foundation does. But it’s a tricky balance and you need to make sure the places you visit with animals in effect in captivity are the right ones. 

We fly home overnight tonight and will hopefully be back home home mid morning! Fingers crossed for flight connections that work! 

Not spent a New Years Day like this before.

It’s also January so I’m trying to be better at exercising and eating well but that all adds a pressure doesn’t it. 

However today will put all that into perspective. I’ve got an enormous amount to fit into today - including new braces for Lil, run training for the twins, and meetings that don’t quite line up with those things, but in the middle of the day I’m going with Lily to a funeral. Yesterday I had a walk and talk with a lovely friend. We got through most of our agenda, put the world to rights, ranted, laughed and even ticked some jobs off our lists. It’s always good to catch up with friends even if it’s short and sweet! #walkandtalk #walkandtalktherapy #walking #walkingaround #friendship #walkingisgoodforthesoul

If you’re looking for somewhere to catch the first glimpses of spring, walk the dog, or simply let the kids burn off some energy this half term, we recommend Trentham Gardens, Stoke-on-Trent.

725 acres of gardens with so much to see and do. The kids loved the walk around the lake, the adventure playground, and spotting the lovely fairies - there are 21 to spot in total. If we hadn’t have eaten lunch already, we’d have definitely booked one of their pods for a picnic - the afternoon teas looked delightful. 

Once fully open, you can brave their maze, take the miniature train ride alongside the lake, enjoy a boat trip and take part in the UK’s first barefoot walking trail. 

Make time to stroll around the makers market when it’s on. Sample and browse award winning local food and drink and some lovely arts and crafts too. Trentham Shopping  Village and Trentham Monkey Forest are also on the estate if you want to make a full day of it.

ad| With huge thanks to @originaltravel for organising this trip with @ateliersdailleurs this morning in #marrakech An authentic pottery workshop with Mr Mohammed who has been making pottery in this location since he was 24 and he’s slightly older than that now. There was two basic electric potters wheels and two manual ones you had to climb into! I should perhaps of been wearing long trousers rather than a long dress to attempt to do that! The result was fairly amusing. Mr Mohammed and our guide from @ateliersdailleurs were really kind in the way they showed us how to make our pots and how they assisted us when we couldn’t quite do it. Although tbf Dad and Lily were the best! I’d highly recommend this activity if you’re in Marrakech with kids 9+ - it’s rustic, fun and gives you a real insight into how the pots you might buy in the souls are made! Lots of similar options available with @originaltravel including mosaic making which was just next door! 

#marrakech #morocco #pottery #familytravel #authentic #africatravel #palmeraie

Had an amazing afternoon today at the home of @bertaouch (aka Mama TouTou) who warmly welcomed us into her home. The cookery workshop was organised by @ateliersdailleurs who focus on social enterprise in Marrakech - employing female tour guides and ensuring that women can work in their home too, using their amazing in this case cooking skills! 

We learned how to cook Moroccan flatbread and aubergine salad, followed by an amazing chicken tagine which everyone LOVED. Lily voted it the best bread and chicken she had ever tasted! 

We’re into the Medina itself tomorrow and wondering if I can buy myself one of the amazing Kaftans Mama TooToo persuaded us to try on! 

#cookerycourse #marrakech #morocco #familytravel

Afternoon trip out to @jardinmajorellemarrakech and the small Berber museum inside. The last time I visited in October the temperature was 35 degrees plus - today was slightly different, hovering around 14! The garden itself though was the same beautiful space. Designed by Jaques Majorelle and then restored in the eighties by Yves Saint Laurent and his partner Pierre Bergé.

We got dropped off by a taxi just before our booked slot (booking essential) at 2.30pm and arranged him to pick his up at 4pm which was the perfect amount of time to do the garden and the small museum.

#marrakech #morocco #jardinmajorelle #yvessaintlaurent #gardens #familytravel #exploredreamdiscover

Popped into the Medina this morning on the free bus from the hotel and went to visit the Bahia Palace. The sun shone and the colours were incredible. It was very very busy though despite us being there for 11ish. They do advise you getting there as soon as it opens at 10 or when it’s closing. When we left at midday the queue to get in was much longer. Heading back to the hotel for lunch now for some quieter time and then heading back into the median for an evening tour with Abdul from @yallaletsgotravel - souks here we come!

#marrakech #bahiapalace #moroc #morroco #familytravel #family #februaryhalfterm

Finished off our week in Marrakech with an afternoon into evening tour of the Medina with Abdul from @yallaletsgotravel - we explored places we would never have found alone including an underground bread oven used by many of the local bakeries, the oldest alley in Marrakech from the 11th century,  a huge fireplace to heat the local hammam. We went right into the souks and wandered through all the different areas including leather, light, metal and rugs. We then bought bags and purses from the local women’s collective directly from them. We finished the tour with tea on a balcony overlooking Jemma El Fna. It was the perfect end to our week in Marrakech.

#marrakech #morocco #moroccotravel #guideinmarrakech #familytravel #exploredreamdiscover

Residence Ca’Foscolo 🇮🇹

Quite a few of you have asked where we stayed in Venice so Eve made a reel for me to show you.

@residence_ca_foscolo is perfectly located. 5 minutes from the Rialto water bus stop and 5 minutes from St Mark’s square too. It was also just round the corner from two great restaurants that we enjoyed: make a booking if you visit them too as the queues were huge when we ate in them. @1000gourmet with great reasonably priced pizzas. I had an amazing tuna and caramelised onion one. Kids had margheritas and also @lapiazzavenezia, more expensive but more options and lovely service. 

We booked a 2 bedroom apartment with a sofa bed in the lounge. The apartment was on the second floor (no lift if that’s an issue) and in a beautiful old building. Rooms were fairly basic and not modern but comfy and clean/ There was a small continental breakfast included, together with Nespresso coffee and milk. The apartment was cleaned every day and the breakfast bits we had used were replaced. It was the perfect place for us to stay as it all allowed us to pop back during the day when we needed to re-charge. We also didn’t need to drag our suitcases too far from the water boat/water taxi. 

Reception is only open 9-2 but if you arrive after that you get a key code and what’s app instructions. It was all really easy. 

Like everywhere you stay in Venice it was not cheap. But as a family of 5 we always have to book two hotel rooms so it worked out much better value for us and we also had more space. 

I’d definitely recommend it if you’re travelling to Venice with kids and want a little extra space. It’s in an excellent location!

Argiroupoli 

I feel a bit mean saying Argiroupoli wasn’t for us but we just got it wrong. The taxi driver yesterday evening recommended it as something to do on a hot day, but we should have gone for lunch or dinner not after, and here’s why.

The mountainous village of Argiroupoli (Argyroupoli) lies 26 km southwest of Rethymno and is famed for its waterfalls and streams. What we didn’t know is that all said waterfalls are in areas claimed by restaurants, and so you need to be eating in them to get close to them.

It’s also a bit odd to see these huge fish in tiny tanks with waterfalls pouring onto them: just my view. 

We found the chapel where water flows from and I can imagine how in ancient times this was seen as a gift from god in arid Crete, but it didn’t tell you anything about it. 

There was lots and lots of people around and it was clearly a very popular tourist attraction. 

For us though the place wasn’t something that we really ‘got’. We wandered around for a while and then left for a cold swimming pool instead! You win some and lose some!

ad| It’s the most magical time of the year and Lucy and family went to @magicalwoodland last night in @visitblakemere - find out what they thought! 

Now I have been to my fair share of Christmas light trails and I'm going to get straight to the point - this one is stunning. Everything you could wish for to create truly unforgettable memories right here at the Magical Woodland at Blakemere Village in Cheshire. 

The festive magic will run from 24th November to 24th December. Tickets are allocated by staggered trail start times and digital tickets received via email are accepted. 

Around 1 mile long, we'd recommend allowing approximately 1.5 hours to enjoy the experience and spend time eating 'grub in the woods' in the outdoor food court equipped with music and multiple open fires for toasting marshmallows. It took 1 adult, a tween and a 7 year old just over an hour to walk the trail and we then spent 30-45 minutes in the food court.

This year was a first taking a tween so I was apprehensive about how well it would go. I had nothing to worry about. We fully immersed ourselves into the magic of Christmas. Walking in a daze through dazzling cathedral canopies of fairy lights, captivating Borealis-style lasers and clouds of flying lanterns was everything we'd hoped for and more.

In fact it was AMAZING. Of all the light trails I have experienced over the last decade; this was truly a favourite and one that I will most definitely be looking out for to kick-start the Christmas season next year. The weather was perfectly still, the moon shone brightly in a completely clear sky and whilst it was freezing (literally freezing point), the whole evening was perfect. The trail is woodland so terrain will differ significantly depending on the weather. I know we struck lucky with our excellently timed visit. The attention to detail was spectacular and the trail was so varied with many different themes as you navigate your way round. 

Highly recommended - go and book tickets! 🎟️ https://minitravellers.co.uk/magical-woodland/

#mammamiatheparty #mammamia #london #abbaparty #o2

What a day we had at @mammamiapartyuk - loads of questions on Facebook about it and by DM on here so I’ll try and answer as many as I can:

1. Yes it’s super expensive, tickets start from £95pp and go up to £200pp for better seats and weekend pricing. 

2. It’s 4 hours long. We did 12pm-4pm. You can also do 7pm-11pm.

3. It’s includes a 4 course meal in the ticket price and a welcome drink. You pay for other drinks on top. 

4. Yes it’s suitable for kids if they love Mamma Mia and can enjoy 4 hours of music. So only you know if your kids will do that.

5. You pay the same price for kids so again, only book if you know they will LOVE it.

6. It doesn’t follow the same story as @mammamiamusical or the film but it’s a similar idea.

7. We did the afternoon show in a day trip from Liverpool. Long day but good fun and reduced our overall cost as we didn’t have to include hotel costs. We also booked a family advance train ticket.

8. It’s really easy to get to the O2 arena where it is from central London on the tube. We did some shopping beforehand.

9. Doors opened at 12pm but queue started to form beforehand. I wish we had joined the queue earlier. You will be sharing a table so if you want better placing, join the queue early.

10. There is a free cloakroom on the way in for all your bags and coats. We left slightly before 4pm and didn’t have to wait too long to collect our bags.

11. It’s brilliant 🤩 really really good fun. 

12. All 5 of us loved it, even if Matt was only one of about 30 men in the whole place.
